'!' marks the creation of a variable
- !user 
  creates a variable with the name of user

'->' is how you assign values to variables
- !user -> 'nesboldt'
  gives the variable 'user' the value of 'nesboldt'

'?' is how you print to the console
- ?'nesboldt' 
  will print 'nesboldt' to the console

'&' is how you start an 'if' statement (use {} for the block)
- & score > 90 { ?'A' }
  checks if score is greater than 90

'?&' is how you do an 'else if' (automatically closes the previous block)
- ?& score > 70 { ?'B' }
  used after an '&' block to check a second condition

'::' is how you do an 'else' (automatically closes the previous block)
- :: { ?'F' }
  runs if the previous '&' or '?&' conditions were false

-note for if/else statments, for the 'if' statment, you do not need to close the {} when adding the else statement
  ex. & score > 90 { ?'A'
      ?& score > 80 { ?'B'
      :: { ?'failure' }

'@' is how you create a loop
- @ 5 { ?'hello' }
  will print 'hello' to the console 5 times

'~' is how you create a function (use {} for functions)
- ~greet { ?'hello' }
  greet()
  - will create a function named greet, that, when called, will print 'hello' to the console

- you can also just have functions return values
  ~greet { return 'hello' }
  ?greet()
  - will print 'hello' to the console

'##' is how you signify comments
- ##this will do nothing
  will do nothing but give you a reminder about what a certain line of code does, etc.
